{{refimprove|date=July 2015}} <!-- Commented out: [[File:Anvaya.jpeg|thumbnail|right|Logo ]] -->
'''Anvaya''' is a [[Khmer people|Khmer]] association established in 2010 with a self-described mission to "bring together and support the returning movement of scattered [[Ethnic groups in Cambodia|Cambodians]] from overseas". Anaya is an independent, non-political, non-profit organization. It is an active organization within Cambodia and in countries with a Cambodian population that has been scattered.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phnompenhpost.com/lift/anvaya-ngo-helps-cambo-dians-return-and-thrive|title=Anvaya: ngo helps cambo dians return and thrive|author=Post Staff|work=Phnom Penh Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asialifemagazine.com/cambodia/returning-overseas-cambodians/|title=Returning overseas Cambodians|work=AsiaLIFE Cambodia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/09/11/travel/phnom-penh-travel-cnngo/|title=Phnom Penh: Asia's next cosmopolitan star?|author=Karla Cripps, CNN|date=11 September 2013|work=CNN}}</ref>
Anvaya has over 300 registered members, collectively called “Anvayiste” or "Diaspora", across the world.
== Origin of name and emblem == The name Anvaya (in Khmer script: អន្វយៈ) comes from the [[Sanskrit]] language and means family or lineage. The Anvaya’s emblem is a set of three lotus flowers, each symbolizing one of the continents of the Diaspora (Europe, America, or Oceania) which together represent Cambodia.{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}
== Creation == Anvaya was created in 2010 by [[Soreasmey Ke Bin]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leshommes.biz/repatriates-cambodia-soreasmey-ke-bin/|title=Repatriates in Cambodia: Soreasmey Ke Bin|work=Les Hommes}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Garrigue|first1=Anne|title=On Asia's new frontier, 40 French entrepreneurs in the East|url=http://issuu.com/magazineasies/docs/40_francais_qui_entreprennent}}</ref> a French-Cambodian, and [[David Yim]], a Cambodian-American. Upon returning to Cambodia in the early 2000s, they observed that Cambodians that wished to return to their roots had no kind of support system to help them. They then launched Anvaya as a free social network to gather people looking to return to their roots at regular events.{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}
In 2013, Anvaya became a fully legal registered association established by Soreasmey Ke Bin, its founding president.{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}
In 2013, Anvaya was legally registered as an association by its president, Soreasmey Ke Bin.{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}
== Organization == Anvaya is managed by a steering committee of 6 directors, each of which are elected by 30 members of the permanent council of the association with a two-year mandate. As of August 2016, the president of the association is one of the original co-founders, Soreasmey Ke Bin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cambodianallianceforthearts.com/soreasmey-ke-bin-founder-of-anvaya-initiative/|title=Soreasmey Ke Bin - Founder of Anvaya Initiative|work=Cambodian Alliance for the Arts}}</ref>
== Mission == The main goal of Anvaya is to "ease the return of the Cambodian diaspora".<ref>A duty to our Homeland, a tribune by Mitty Steele, Anvaya's vice-president http://www.banyanblog.com/home/a-duty-to-our-homeland</ref> Anvaya's 4 key objectives are to:{{citation needed|date=July 2015}} * Foster a sense of community among returnees through this social and professional network * Encourage and support overseas Cambodians in their effort to return * Inform overseas Cambodian about business, social and employment opportunities in Cambodia * Develop opportunities for overseas Cambodians to return, especially young professionals Anvaya aspires to catalyze and facilitate the rebirth of Cambodia through the collaboration and support of partners in the private sector, international institutions and government.
== Members == All the members of Anvaya originate from Cambodia and have lived among the Cambodian diaspora communities. They may be in Cambodia or overseas.{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}
In March 2015, Anvaya had 300 members. Since the beginning of its official registration, Anvaya has counted on the support and the membership of leading characters of the Diaspora, such as the Cambodian society. Current prominent members include: * Two Cambodian government ministers: [[Sun Chanthol]], Minister of trade; and Dr. Ing Khantha Phavi, Minister of Women * French-Cambodian film directors and producers, [[Rithy Panh]], [[Davy Chou]], and Visal Sok * Artists like Peap Tarr, Fonki, the cartoonist Séra, and singers such as Tony Keo (Canadian) and Laura Mam (USA) * Professional athletic members include Tep Rivihit, the general secretary of the Cambodian tennis federation and the N°1 Cambodian professional tennis player [[Bun Kenny|Kenny Bun]] (French), as well as French-Khmer football/soccer players [[Thierry Bin|Thierry Chantha Bin,]] and Boris Kok.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leshommes.biz/boris-myagui-kok/|title=Repatriates in Cambodia: Boris Myagui Kok|work=Les Hommes}}</ref> * Pily Wong, the former president of the French Chamber of Commerce, is an Anvaya counselor. * Entrepreneur and investor [[Thierry Tea]]<nowiki/> is the founder of the PhilJets Group<ref>{{cite web|url=http://manilastandardtoday.com/2015/06/07/aviation-s-cup-of-tea/ |title=Aviation’s cup of Tea - The Standard |publisher=Manilastandardtoday.com |date=2015-06-07 |accessdate=2016-01-21}}</ref> and Agama Investments,<ref>{{cite web|last=Insider |first=Management |url=http://www.managementinsider.asia/flying-high/ |title=FLYING HIGH &#124; Management Insider |publisher=Managementinsider.asia |date=2015-06-01 |accessdate=2016-01-21}}</ref> People of the Year awardee in the Philippines, and also a Foreign Trade Adviser for France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cce-phils.com/officers.php |title=CCE - Liste des CCE |publisher=Cce-phils.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-21}}</ref> * The current president of Anvaya, Soreasmey Ke Bin, is also the secretary general of the French Chamber of Commerce
== Financing == The association is financed by donations and membership fees. In 2015 the French Member of Parliament, [[Thierry Mariani]] subsidized Anvaya on his diplomatic reserve.{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}
== Activities == Anvaya has several types of activities to support their members in Cambodia and overseas, including: * An Afterwork event every second Thursday for members residing in Cambodia, * A monthly dinner revolving around Cambodian personalities from the government or from Cambodian society, including the French Ambassador, Mr. [[Jean-Claude Poimboeuf]], the director [[Rithy Panh]], the deputy [[Hun Many]] or the deputy from the opposition, [[Mu Sochua]].{{citation needed|date=July 2015}} * Symposiums on the purpose of the Diaspora at the French Institute of Cambodia in July 2012 and April 2013,{{citation needed|date=July 2015}} * Khmer courses, both oral and literature, for Anvaya members in Phnom Penh,{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}
Anvaya also holds regular cultural and sporting outings. Some examples include: * Members accompanied Father François Ponchuaud to recall the events of April 1975, * Treks and outings in the forest such as tree planting or environmental-site cleaning projects to support community development.{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}
Anvaya furthermore has a football team in Phnom Penh, called Anvaya Keila, which may be replicated in Lyon (France). Besides this, some Anvaya members{{who|date=September 2016}} are distinguishing themselves in different sport competitions (tennis, half-marathon etc.…){{citation needed|date=July 2015}}
== Relationship with authorities == Although Anvaya is non-political, it keeps a strong open dialogue with Cambodian authorities within the government. For example, in October 2012, Anvaya went to the Royal Palace to pay tribute to the [[Norodom Sihanouk|King Father Norodom Sihanouk]]. Anvaya was invited to this time of remembrance by [[Norodom Ranariddh|Prince Norodom Ranariddh]] to be present in the capacity of an element of the civil society.<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U9Zp4790zd8|title=ANVAYA - Last respect to King Father 26/10/12|date=28 October 2012|work=YouTube}}</ref> A MOU was signed in March 2014 with the Cambodian Olympic Committee in which Anvaya was to recruit athletes from Diaspora for future sporting events such as the [[Southeast Asian Games|SEA Games]] and the Olympic games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phnompenhpost.com/sport/mou-help-find-medalists|title=MoU to help find medalists|author=Dan Riley|work=Phnom Penh Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.noccambodia.org/website/read.php?lang=en&id=1286|title=MOU Signing Ceremony Between NOCC and ANVAYA|author=Cheth, Dara|work=noccambodia.org}}</ref>
In November 2013, Anvaya signed an agreement with the French Embassy to build a memorial for the victims of the Khmer Rouge. The monument was designed by Ing Séra, a French-Cambodian artist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phnompenhpost.com/7days/sculptor-plans-genocide-memorial-historic-french-embassy-grounds|title=Sculptor plans genocide memorial for historic French embassy grounds|author=Emily Wight|work=Phnom Penh Post}}</ref> The project was recognized by the Extraordinary Chambers in the Courts of Cambodia as a meaningful reparation for Khmer Rouge victims.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eccc.gov.kh/en/articles/meaningful-reparation-khmer-rouge-victims|title=Meaningful reparation for Khmer Rouge victims|work=Extraordinary Chambers in the Courts of Cambodia (ECCC)}}</ref> The construction started in summer 2015, a first piece has been installed in June 2017, and the official inauguration is planned for October 2017.
== Anvaya Reatrei == In March 2015, Anvaya organized its first Gala known as Anvaya Reatrei. This event gathered more than 150 people and awarded the "Members of the Year". [[Rithy Panh]] was awarded "Best Director", and [[Thierry Bin|Thierry Chantha Bin]] was awarded "Best Athlete". The French-Cambodian Borany Mam was awarded the best activist for her association ASPK and their efforts to restore and protect the painting at the National Museum of Phnom Penh. Tony Keo, a Canadian singer, won an award for musical performance. American-Cambodian Chanda Hun won "Best Entrepreneur", and Peap Tarr won "Best Designer".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khmertimeskh.com/news/10003/what---s-happening-in-phnom-penh/|title=What’s Happening in Phnom Penh|work=Khmer Times - News Portal Cambodia -}}</ref>
